sentence: US equity benchmarks were trading lower at mid-day on Tuesday as a decline in consumer confidence hit trading sentiment amid an onslaught of mixed earnings results and lower oil prices .

The Conference Board's monthly Consumer Confidence Index, conducted by Nielsen, declined to 98.6 in October from 103.5 in September as consumers' assessments of current business and employment conditions softened.
The Michigan sentiment index, produced by the University of Michigan, also posted a decline, with the latest monthly reading sliding to a 13-month low of 87.9 in October from 91.2 in September.
Oil prices were in retreat as uncertainty regarding the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries' (OPEC) ability to iron out details of a production cut at its November meeting lingered.
The bloc, whose members generate approximately 40% of oil globally, agreed in principle to lower output in September after two years of price erosion caused by over-production.
Precisely how the agreement will be implemented among OPEC's members has yet to be finalised.
Separate data presented a more rosy outlook.
The Richmond Fed manufacturing index edged up to -4 in October after improving slightly to -8 in September from -11 in August.
And, the Case-Shiller home price index rose by 0.42% in August to 191.66 for the 20-City index after a 0.56% gain in July to 190.85.

In equities, shares in Proctor & Gamble ( PG ) were 4.2% higher after the producer of packaged consumer goods posted fiscal first quarter adjusted earnings of $1.03 per share compared with an income $0.98 per share a year ago, beating the consensus estimate of analysts polled by Capital IQ for $0.98.
Merck ( MRK ) was 1.2% higher after further increasing its 2016 earnings guidance, following better-than-expected results for the third quarter.

Technology company 3M ( MMM ) was 3.2% lower after the manufacturing conglomerate reported third quarter earnings just above street view and sales just below expectations, Caterpiller ( CAT ) was down by 1.1% after the manufacturer of mining and construction equipment reported mixed third quarter results and lowered its guidance on FY16 revenue below analysts' forecasts.
And, science and technology company DuPont was 0.9% lower despite increasing its earnings outlook for 2016 after posting better-than-expected results for the third quarter.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was 0.23% lower, the Standard & Poor's 500 was down by 0.28% and the Nasdaq was down by 0.38% at the time of writing.
In Europe, the Stoxx 600 closed 0.43% lower, the FTSE finished 0.34% higher, Frankfurt's DAX finished 0.13% lower and Paris' CAC-40 was down by 0.40%.
